==Merged second translation==
'''Tsushima Faith''' (津島信仰) refers to a [[Shinto]] faith centered on {{ill|Tsushima Shrine|ja|津島神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsushima Shrine|qq=}}, located primarily in [[Tsushima, Aichi|Tsushima City]], [[Aichi Prefecture]], and distributed mainly throughout the [[Tōkai region]].

This faith is dedicated to {{ill|Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|スサノオ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo-no-Mikoto|qq=}} and {{ill|Gozu Tennō|ja|牛頭天王|1=Gozu Tennō|1=Gozu Tennō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gozu Tennō|13=User:Immanuelle/Gozu Tennō|qq=}} and is a variety of {{ill|Gion Faith|lt=Gion Faith|lt=Gion faith|ja|祇園信仰|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gion faith|qq=}}. However, Tsushima faith also possesses unique characteristics,<ref>{{Cite journal|和書|author=松山由布子 |title=津島神社所蔵『牛頭天王講式』と奥三河伝来『牛頭天王五段式』の関わりについて |journal=愛知県史研究 |issn=1883-3799 |publisher=愛知県 |year=2017 |volume=21 |pages=57-72 |naid=130007696076 |doi=10.24707/aichikenshikenkyu.21.0_57 |url=https://doi.org/10.24707/aichikenshikenkyu.21.0_57 |accessdate=2021-07-01}}</ref> with the {{ill|Owari Tsushima Tennō Festival|ja|尾張津島天王祭|lt=Tsushima Festival|lt_ja=津島祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Owari Tsushima Tennō Festival|qq=}} representing one of its main events.<ref>{{Cite journal|和書|author=黒田一充 |title=津島信仰のお仮屋 |journal=関西大学博物館紀要 |issn=1341-4895 |publisher=関西大学博物館 |year=2009 |month=mar |issue=15 |pages=1-17 |naid=110007334592 |url=https://hdl.handle.net/10112/2887 |accessdate=2021-07-01}}</ref>

== Overview ==
In {{ill|Nagoya|ja|名古屋市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagoya|qq=}}, Susanoo and Gozu Tennō are referred to as "Otennō-sama." Religious associations called "Tsushima Daisan-kō" were established, with representatives making pilgrimages to Tsushima Shrine to receive sacred amulets (ofuda) for distribution among members. Over time, shrines dedicated to Tsushima Shrine were established within neighborhoods, eventually leading to the "Roof God" (屋根神様, yane-gami-sama) practice, in which shrines for Gozu Tennō were placed on household rooftops.

The emblem (神紋) of Susanoo and Gozu Tennō is the {{ill|Mokko crest|ja|木瓜紋|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mokko crest|qq=}}. The {{ill|Oda clan|ja|織田家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oda clan|qq=}}, based in the Tōkai region and devotees of Tsushima Shrine, also used the mokko crest, linking the two prominently.<ref>{{Cite journal|和書|author=赤木妙子 |title=織田信長の自己神格化と津嶋牛頭天王 |url=https://koara.lib.keio.ac.jp/xoonips/modules/xoonips/detail.php?koara_id=AN00100104-19910400-0127 |journal=史学 |issn=03869334 |publisher=三田史学会 |year=1991 |month=apr |volume=60 |issue=1 |pages=127-140 |naid=110007410625 |accessdate=2021-07-01}}</ref>

== Tsushima Shrines Nationwide ==
Shrines established through bunrei (spirit division) from Tsushima Shrine number about 3,000 across Japan, mainly concentrated in the Tōkai region. Many were originally named "Gozu Tennō Shrine" or "Tennō Shrine," but following the Meiji-period separation of Shinto and Buddhism, the head shrine (originally Tsushima Gozu Tennō Shrine) was renamed Tsushima Shrine, prompting others to follow suit.

=== Head Shrine ===
* {{ill|Tsushima Shrine|ja|津島神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsushima Shrine|qq=}} – Located in Tsushima City, Aichi Prefecture; head shrine of Tsushima faith.

